description.narrative: By 2020, health workers at community and primary care level have increased capacity to identify, enroll and treat children with severe acute malnutrition, which contributes to Community-Based Management Of Acute Malnutrition, Nutrition And Emergencies, Treatment Of Severe Acute Malnutrition, Treatment Of Severe Acute Malnutrition (Covid). UNICEF aims to achieve this through Evaluations, Research And Data, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: By 2020, people, particularly women and young children, more equitably access and use quality health and nutrition services.

description.narrative:
UNICEF Mozambique has continued its support for developing a wider scale-up of the national management of acute malnutrition. UNICEF has facilitated the evaluation of the community-based management of Acute Malnutrition program and helped improve quality of inpatient management with the national paediatric association (AMOPE). Humanitarian demands have been considerable higher in 2019 due to multiple emergencies like drought, 2 cyclones, and nutrition insecure districts. UNICEF has helped on the consolidation of a systematic approach based on the Integrate Phase classification (IPC) on Acute Malnutrition system to assess and respond to humanitarian situations.
